name: 9-Anthrylmethanol
Reason: The basic unit we can start considering is anthracene, which has a melting point of about 216 degrees Celsius. Introducing a hydroxymethyl (-CH2OH) group causes the following effects: 1) The -OH (hydroxyl) group is capable of hydrogen bonding, which usually increases the melting point due to stronger intermolecular forces. This can add about +40 to the melting value. However, 2) The addition of a -CH2- (methylene) group slightly reduces the planarity and symmetry of the molecule, thus potentially weakening the pi-pi stacking interactions characteristic of polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs), which may decrease the melting point. This could decrease the melting point by approximately -20. 3) The -CH2OH group also increases the molecular weight which slightly increases the melting point, contributing a possible increase of +10. So, the overall effect of adding a hydroxymethyl group to anthracene is a predicted net change of about (+40 - 20 + 10) = +30 to the melting point.
Prediction: The predicted melting point of 9-anthrylmethanol would then be 216 (anthracene) + 30 (net change due to -CH2OH) = 246 degrees Celsius.
